```rust
pub trait Display {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut Formatter<'_>) -> Result;
}
```
Format trait for an empty format, `{}`. Implementing this trait enables the type to be printed with `println!`, `format!`, etc.

```rust
pub trait Debug {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut Formatter<'_>) -> Result;
}
```
Format trait for the `{:?}` formatter. Should output a useful debugging representation. Can be automatically derived with `#[derive(Debug)]`.

```rust
pub trait Clone {
    fn clone(&self) -> Self;
    fn clone_from(&mut self, source: &Self) { ... }
}
```
A trait for types that can explicitly duplicate themselves. Differs from `Copy` in that `Clone` can be expensive and is explicit.

```rust
pub trait Default {
    fn default() -> Self;
}
```
A trait for giving a type a useful default value. Can be derived for structs where all fields implement `Default`.

```rust
pub trait PartialEq<Rhs: ?Sized = Self> {
    fn eq(&self, other: &Rhs) -> bool;
    fn ne(&self, other: &Rhs) -> bool { ... }
}
```
Trait for equality comparisons which are partial equivalence relations. Allows `==` and `!=` operators.

```rust
pub trait PartialOrd<Rhs: ?Sized = Self>: PartialEq<Rhs> {
    fn partial_cmp(&self, other: &Rhs) -> Option<Ordering>;
}
```
Trait for values that can be compared for a sort-order. Enables `<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=` operators.

```rust
pub trait Ord: Eq + PartialOrd<Self> {
    fn cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> Ordering;
}
```
Trait for types that form a total order. All values can be compared and the comparison is consistent.

```rust
pub trait Hash {
    fn hash<H: Hasher>(&self, state: &mut H);
}
```
A hashable type. Types implementing `Hash` can be used as `HashMap` keys or `HashSet` elements.

```rust
pub trait Iterator {
    type Item;
    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item>;
}
```
A trait for dealing with iterators. Only the `next` method is required; all other methods have default implementations built on `next`.

```rust
pub trait From<T> {
    fn from(value: T) -> Self;
}
```
Used for value-to-value conversions. Implementing `From<T> for U` automatically provides `Into<U> for T`.

```rust
pub trait Into<T> {
    fn into(self) -> T;
}
```
A conversion trait. Usually you implement `From` instead, which gives `Into` for free via blanket impl.

```rust
pub trait AsRef<T: ?Sized> {
    fn as_ref(&self) -> &T;
}
```
Cheap reference-to-reference conversions. Used to make APIs accept multiple reference types.

```rust
pub trait Deref {
    type Target: ?Sized;
    fn deref(&self) -> &Self::Target;
}
```
Used for immutable dereferencing operations. Allows smart pointers to behave like references. Enables deref coercion.

```rust
pub trait Drop {
    fn drop(&mut self);
}
```
Custom code within the destructor. Called when a value goes out of scope. Used for resource cleanup like closing files or freeing memory.

```rust
pub trait Fn<Args>: FnMut<Args> {
    extern "rust-call" fn call(&self, args: Args) -> Self::Output;
}
```
A version of the call operator that takes an immutable receiver. Closures that only capture by immutable reference implement `Fn`.

```rust
pub trait FnMut<Args>: FnOnce<Args> {
    extern "rust-call" fn call_mut(&mut self, args: Args) -> Self::Output;
}
```
A version of the call operator that takes a mutable receiver. Closures that capture by mutable reference implement `FnMut`.

```rust
pub trait FnOnce<Args> {
    type Output;
    extern "rust-call" fn call_once(self, args: Args) -> Self::Output;
}
```
A version of the call operator that takes a by-value receiver. All closures implement `FnOnce`; if they move captured values, they only implement `FnOnce`.
